window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["electrocardiography"]={"slug": "electrocardiography", "title": "Electrocardiography", "tagline": "A systematic, fellowship-depth approach to reading the 12-lead ECG — rate, rhythm, axis, intervals, blocks, and chambers — anchored by a precise library of named ischemic and morphologic signs that change disposition at the bedside.", "level": 1, "readMin": 40, "takeaways": ["A disciplined, identical sequence on every tracing — rate, rhythm, axis, intervals, hypertrophy/chambers, then ischemia and named patterns — is what prevents the single most common ECG error, which is anchoring on the obvious abnormality and missing the lethal one.", "Several benign-appearing tracings are STEMI-equivalents that mandate emergent reperfusion despite the absence of classic ST elevation: de Winter T waves, Wellens syndrome, posterior MI, and a Sgarbossa-positive or modified-Sgarbossa-positive LBBB or paced rhythm.", "The QT interval is the highest-yield interval to protect: correct it (Bazett, or Fridericia at rates far from 60), keep QTc under 500 ms when stacking QT-prolonging agents, and treat torsades with intravenous magnesium and rate acceleration rather than additional antiarrhythmics.", "Mobitz II and third-degree AV block localize to the infranodal His-Purkinje system, do not respond reliably to atropine, and are Class I indications for permanent pacing absent a reversible cause, whereas Mobitz I (Wenckebach) is usually nodal and benign.", "Named morphologic signs — Brugada type 1, epsilon wave, Osborn/J wave, electrical alternans, prominent U waves, Ashman phenomenon, digoxin effect — each map to a specific channelopathy, structural disease, electrolyte derangement, or drug, and recognizing them on sight collapses a broad differential to a single diagnosis."], "references": ["AHA/ACCF/HRS Recommendations for the Standardization and Interpretation of the Electrocardiogram (Scientific Statement series, Parts I-VI, Circulation 2007-2009)", "Fourth Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction (Thygesen K et al., ESC/ACC/AHA/WHF, Circulation 2018)", "2018 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline on the Evaluation and Management of Patients With Bradycardia and Cardiac Conduction Delay (JACC 2019)", "2017 AHA/ACC/HRS Guideline for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death", "2015 HRS/EHRA/APHRS Expert Consensus Statement on the Diagnosis and Management of Patients With Inherited Primary Arrhythmia Syndromes", "de Winter RJ, Verouden NJ, Wellens HJJ, Wilde AAM. A New ECG Sign of Proximal LAD Occlusion. New England Journal of Medicine, 2008", "Sgarbossa EB et al. Electrocardiographic Diagnosis of Evolving Acute Myocardial Infarction in the Presence of Left Bundle-Branch Block. New England Journal of Medicine, 1996", "Smith SW et al. Diagnosis of ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction in the Presence of Left Bundle Branch Block With the ST-Elevation to S-Wave Ratio (Modified Sgarbossa Criteria). Annals of Emergency Medicine, 2012", "Ortiz M et al. Randomized comparison of intravenous procainamide vs amiodarone for stable well-tolerated wide QRS complex tachycardia (PROCAMIO). European Heart Journal, 2017", "The Digitalis Investigation Group (DIG). The Effect of Digoxin on Mortality and Morbidity in Patients With Heart Failure. New England Journal of Medicine, 1997"], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This module builds the reading discipline of a cardiology fellow: a fixed interpretive sequence applied to every tracing, plus a working memory of the named patterns that change disposition in minutes. The goal is not pattern-matching alone but understanding <strong>why</strong> each sign points where it does."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Apply an invariant six-step interpretive sequence to any 12-lead ECG.", "Determine rate, axis, and the three intervals (PR, QRS, QT/QTc) with the shortcuts and the exact numeric thresholds.", "Localize AV block and bundle/fascicular block to nodal versus infranodal tissue and state the pacing implications.", "Recognize the STEMI-equivalent patterns that lack classic ST elevation and act on them.", "Identify the named morphologic signs on sight and map each to its underlying channelopathy, structural disease, electrolyte disturbance, or drug.", "Select and dose the drug classes that either treat or cause the ECG abnormalities in this module."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The organizing principle for the whole module: the ECG has no free parameters. Every deflection is caused by a vector of depolarization or repolarization moving toward or away from a lead. When you read a sign as a <strong>direction and timing of a wavefront</strong> rather than a shape to memorize, the named signs stop being trivia and become deductions."}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why It Matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The ECG remains the fastest, cheapest, and most decision-dense test in cardiovascular medicine. It is the gatekeeper for cath-lab activation, the front line for arrhythmia and channelopathy diagnosis, and the single most misread study in acute care because interpreters anchor on the first abnormality and stop looking."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["A meaningful minority of acute coronary occlusions do not meet classic ST-elevation voltage criteria on the first tracing; several are recognizable only as named equivalents.", "Time-to-reperfusion is prognostic in occlusion MI, so an ECG sign that is recognized in seconds versus missed for an hour is a mortality variable, not an academic point.", "Conduction-system disease and inherited arrhythmia syndromes are frequently first, and sometimes only, detectable on a resting ECG obtained for an unrelated reason."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "The most dangerous ECG is the one read as normal. Always complete the full sequence even after you find the headline abnormality — de Winter T waves, a posterior MI, and a Sgarbossa-positive LBBB are all easy to file under a benign label and send home."}]}, {"id": "systematic-approach", "title": "The Systematic Approach", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Read every ECG the same way, every time. The sequence below is deliberately ordered so that rate and rhythm frame everything downstream, and so that ischemia and named signs are evaluated last, after you already understand the conduction and chamber substrate on which they sit."}, {"type": "steps", "items": ["<strong>Rate.</strong> Atrial and ventricular rates separately if they differ. Use the 300-150-100-75-60-50 rule for regular rhythms, or count QRS complexes in a 6-second strip and multiply by 10 for irregular ones.", "<strong>Rhythm.</strong> Is there a P before every QRS and a QRS after every P? Regular or irregular? Narrow or wide? Establish the atrial rhythm and the AV relationship before naming anything.", "<strong>Axis.</strong> Quadrant method with leads I and aVF, refined by the most isoelectric limb lead. Flag left, right, and extreme (northwest) axis and ask what each implies.", "<strong>Intervals.</strong> PR (120-200 ms), QRS (<120 ms), QT with rate correction. Each abnormal interval has its own differential.", "<strong>Chambers and hypertrophy.</strong> Atrial enlargement from the P wave, ventricular hypertrophy from precordial voltage, with the caveat that voltage criteria are specific but insensitive.", "<strong>Ischemia, infarction, and named patterns.</strong> ST segments and T waves in anatomic groupings, reciprocal change, and the specific named signs — only now, with full context."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Mnemonic — <strong>Rate, Rhythm, Axis, Intervals, Chambers, Ischemia</strong>. Six steps, always in the same order, no exceptions. The fixed order is the safeguard against premature closure."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Two habits separate fellows from residents on the ECG. First, always compare with a prior tracing when one exists — a new finding and an old finding carry entirely different weight. Second, in any acute chest-pain presentation, obtain <strong>serial</strong> ECGs 10-15 minutes apart, because hyperacute and de Winter patterns evolve, and a dynamic tracing is itself a diagnosis."}]}, {"id": "rate-rhythm", "title": "Rate and Rhythm", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Rate and rhythm are inseparable from the AV relationship. The disciplined question is not merely what the rate is but what is driving the atria, what is driving the ventricles, and how the two are coupled."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "300 rule", "def": "For a regular rhythm, divide 300 by the number of large (5 mm) boxes between consecutive R waves. Successive box counts give 300, 150, 100, 75, 60, 50."}, {"term": "6-second rule", "def": "For any rhythm, especially irregular ones such as atrial fibrillation, count QRS complexes in a 6-second strip and multiply by 10 (or a 10-second strip times 6)."}, {"term": "AV dissociation", "def": "Atria and ventricles beat independently. Seen in complete heart block and in ventricular tachycardia, and a key discriminator in wide-complex tachycardia."}]}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "items": ["<strong>Regular narrow-complex tachycardia:</strong> sinus tachycardia, atrial flutter with fixed conduction, AVNRT, AVRT, atrial tachycardia. Adenosine or vagal maneuvers unmask the atrial activity.", "<strong>Irregularly irregular:</strong> atrial fibrillation, multifocal atrial tachycardia (three or more distinct P morphologies), or atrial flutter with variable block.", "<strong>Regular wide-complex tachycardia:</strong> assume ventricular tachycardia until proven otherwise, especially with structural heart disease or prior infarct."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Atrial flutter hides at a ventricular rate near 150 with 2:1 conduction because only every other flutter wave is obvious. Any regular narrow tachycardia at almost exactly 150 should prompt a hunt for flutter waves in II, III, aVF and V1, or a diagnostic dose of adenosine to slow AV conduction and reveal them."}]}, {"id": "axis-hemiblocks", "title": "Axis and the Hemiblocks", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The mean frontal-plane QRS axis is the net direction of ventricular depolarization. It is read from the limb leads and interpreted as a quadrant, then refined. Axis matters because a shift is often the first and only clue to a fascicular block, chamber enlargement, or an acute right-heart event."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Axis", "Range", "Lead I", "Lead aVF", "Common causes"], "rows": [["Normal", "-30 to +90 deg", "Positive", "Positive", "Normal heart"], ["Left axis deviation", "-30 to -90 deg", "Positive", "Negative", "LAFB, inferior MI, LVH, LBBB"], ["Right axis deviation", "+90 to +180 deg", "Negative", "Positive", "LPFB, RVH, lateral MI, PE, normal in children/thin adults"], ["Extreme (northwest)", "-90 to +/-180 deg", "Negative", "Negative", "VT, hyperkalemia, paced rhythm, lead misplacement"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Mnemonic — quadrant check: <strong>if leads I and aVF both point up, the axis is normal (they agree, all is well)</strong>. If they point away from each other (I up, aVF down) the axis is left; if I is down and aVF up, it is right; both down is extreme. Refine by finding the most isoelectric limb lead — the true axis is perpendicular to it."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Left anterior fascicular block (LAFB)", "def": "Left axis deviation beyond -45 deg, qR complexes in I and aVL, rS complexes in II, III and aVF, with a normal or only slightly widened QRS. The anterior fascicle failing leaves the initial vector pointing down-right and the dominant vector swinging up-left."}, {"term": "Left posterior fascicular block (LPFB)", "def": "Right axis deviation, rS in I and aVL, qR in II, III and aVF, normal QRS width, and only after excluding RVH, lateral MI, and PE. Rare in isolation because the posterior fascicle is short, thick, and dual-supplied."}, {"term": "Bifascicular block", "def": "RBBB plus LAFB (common) or RBBB plus LPFB. Trifascicular disease is inferred when bifascicular block coexists with first-degree AV block, signaling advanced conduction-system disease, though true trifascicular block can only be proven electrophysiologically."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Mnemonic for the hemiblocks — the <strong>Left Anterior</strong> fascicle failing sends the axis <strong>leaving up and to the left</strong> (LAD); the <strong>Left Posterior</strong> fascicle failing sends it <strong>reaching down and to the right</strong> (RAD). Anterior-Left, Posterior-Right pairs the fascicle with the axis it produces."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Illustrated LAFB, LPFB, and bifascicular block tracings with axis vectors.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — fascicular blocks"}]}, {"id": "intervals-qt", "title": "Intervals, QT, and the Long-QT Differential", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Three intervals carry the interpretive load: PR (AV conduction), QRS (ventricular conduction), and QT (repolarization). The QT is the interval fellows are expected to protect, because a prolonged QT is the substrate for torsades de pointes and sudden death, and because it is the interval most often lengthened iatrogenically."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "PR interval", "def": "Normal 120-200 ms. Short PR with a delta wave suggests ventricular pre-excitation (WPW); short PR without a delta wave may be a junctional or low-atrial origin. Long PR is first-degree AV block."}, {"term": "QRS duration", "def": "Normal under 120 ms. 110-120 ms is an incomplete bundle branch block; 120 ms or greater is complete BBB, a fascicular-plus-bundle pattern, pre-excitation, hyperkalemia, or a ventricular rhythm."}, {"term": "QT / QTc", "def": "Measure QT in the lead with the clearest T-wave end (often II or V5) and correct for rate. Bazett: QTc = QT / square-root(RR in seconds). Prolonged above roughly 450 ms (men) or 460-470 ms (women); torsades risk climbs steeply above 500 ms."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Bazett over-corrects at fast rates and under-corrects at slow rates. At heart rates far from 60, prefer Fridericia (QT / cube-root RR) or Framingham correction, and never diagnose a long QT off a single fast-rate Bazett value. Measure over several beats and avoid including a U wave in the QT — the QU interval masquerading as QT is a classic false positive."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Mnemonic for acquired long QT — the <strong>ABCDE drugs</strong>: <strong>A</strong>ntiarrhythmics (sotalol, dofetilide, class IA), <strong>A</strong>ntibiotics (macrolides, fluoroquinolones), anti-psy<strong>C</strong>hotics (haloperidol, ziprasidone), anti-<strong>D</strong>epressants (TCAs, citalopram), anti-<strong>E</strong>metics (ondansetron, droperidol). Add the three electrolytes: low K, low Mg, low Ca all prolong."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Drug class / cause", "Examples", "Mechanism", "Key caution", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Class IA antiarrhythmic", "Quinidine, procainamide, disopyramide", "IKr block plus sodium-channel block", "Avoid with baseline QTc above 450-470 ms", "QTc, drug level, renal function"], ["Class III antiarrhythmic", "Sotalol, dofetilide, ibutilide, amiodarone", "IKr (rapid delayed rectifier) block", "Dofetilide/sotalol contraindicated if CrCl low or QTc above 500 ms; inpatient load for dofetilide", "QTc each dose, K, Mg, CrCl"], ["Macrolide / fluoroquinolone", "Azithromycin, levofloxacin", "IKr block", "Additive with other QT drugs", "QTc if stacking agents"], ["Antipsychotic / antiemetic", "Haloperidol, ondansetron, methadone", "IKr block", "IV haloperidol and methadone are high risk", "Baseline and on-therapy QTc"], ["Electrolyte depletion", "Hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia, hypocalcemia", "Prolonged repolarization", "Common and correctable trigger of TdP", "Replete K to 4.5-5, Mg above 2"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Torsades de pointes with a long QT is treated by <strong>intravenous magnesium 2 g</strong> regardless of the serum level, aggressive potassium repletion to 4.5-5 mmol/L, and removal of the offending drug. For pause-dependent (bradycardia-triggered) torsades, accelerate the rate with isoproterenol or transvenous overdrive pacing to shorten the QT. Do not reach for additional antiarrhythmics — most will worsen it."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Worked examples of QT measurement pitfalls and torsades morphology.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — QT interval and torsades"}]}, {"id": "conduction-blocks", "title": "AV Block and Bundle Branch Block", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The single most consequential localization in conduction disease is nodal versus infranodal. Nodal (AV node) block is usually vagally influenced, atropine-responsive, and benign. Infranodal (His-Purkinje) block is unstable, atropine-unresponsive, and a pacing indication because its escape rhythms are slow and unreliable."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "First-degree AV block", "def": "PR above 200 ms, every P conducts. Usually nodal and benign; rarely symptomatic unless very long (above 300 ms) with AV dyssynchrony."}, {"term": "Second-degree, Mobitz I (Wenckebach)", "def": "Progressive PR prolongation until a P wave is dropped, with the RR interval paradoxically shortening before the pause. Almost always nodal; benign; rarely needs pacing."}, {"term": "Second-degree, Mobitz II", "def": "Fixed PR with a sudden non-conducted P and no preceding PR prolongation, usually with a wide QRS. Infranodal, unstable, and a Class I pacing indication because it progresses unpredictably to complete block."}, {"term": "High-grade AV block", "def": "Two or more consecutive P waves fail to conduct. Treat as infranodal and pace absent a reversible cause."}, {"term": "Third-degree (complete) AV block", "def": "Complete AV dissociation with an independent escape rhythm. A narrow junctional escape (40-60) is more stable than a wide ventricular escape (20-40); both warrant pacing in the absence of a reversible cause."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Distinguishing the second-degree blocks: in <strong>Wenckebach the PR lengthens and then a beat drops; in Mobitz II the PR is a metronome until a beat vanishes without warning</strong>. When 2:1 block makes the pattern ambiguous, a wide QRS, absence of atropine response, and worsening of block with exercise or atropine all point infranodal."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Feature", "LBBB", "RBBB"], "rows": [["QRS width", "120 ms or more", "120 ms or more"], ["V1", "Wide, deep QS or rS (W shape)", "rSR' (M shape, rabbit ears)"], ["V6 / lateral leads", "Broad monophasic R (M shape), no Q", "Wide slurred S wave (W shape)"], ["Septal Q waves (I, V6)", "Absent", "Preserved"], ["Discordant ST/T", "Expected (appropriate discordance)", "In V1-V3 (right precordial)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Mnemonic — <strong>WiLLiaM MaRRoW</strong>: in <strong>L</strong>BBB, V1 looks like a <strong>W</strong> and V6 like an <strong>M</strong> (WiLLiaM). In <strong>R</strong>BBB, V1 looks like an <strong>M</strong> and V6 like a <strong>W</strong> (MaRRoW)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "LBBB fundamentally re-sequences ventricular activation, so it invalidates most standard criteria for LVH, Q-wave infarct, and ordinary ST-segment reading. This is exactly why the Sgarbossa and modified-Sgarbossa criteria exist — they are the sanctioned way to diagnose acute MI within an LBBB or ventricular-paced complex."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Side-by-side LBBB and RBBB morphology across all 12 leads.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — bundle branch block"}]}, {"id": "chambers-hypertrophy", "title": "Chamber Enlargement and Hypertrophy", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Atrial abnormality is read from the P wave in II and V1; ventricular hypertrophy is read from precordial voltage. Voltage criteria are specific but insensitive — their absence never excludes hypertrophy, and their presence in a thin young patient may be a normal variant."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Right atrial enlargement (P pulmonale)", "def": "Tall, peaked P wave of 2.5 mm or more in lead II, or a prominent initial positive component in V1. Classic in pulmonary hypertension and severe tricuspid disease."}, {"term": "Left atrial enlargement (P mitrale)", "def": "Broad (above 120 ms), notched (bifid) P wave in lead II, and a deep, wide terminal-negative component in V1 (at least 1 mm deep and 1 mm wide, the P-terminal force)."}, {"term": "Left ventricular hypertrophy", "def": "Sokolow-Lyon: S in V1 plus R in V5 or V6 of 35 mm or more. Cornell: R in aVL plus S in V3 above 28 mm (men) or above 20 mm (women). R in aVL alone above 11 mm. Often with a lateral strain pattern of down-sloping ST depression and T inversion."}, {"term": "Right ventricular hypertrophy", "def": "Dominant R in V1 (R greater than S), right axis deviation, right precordial T-wave inversion, and often right atrial enlargement. Consider pulmonary hypertension, congenital disease, or chronic PE."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "LVH with a repolarization abnormality (strain) is not the same as ischemia, but the two coexist and the strain pattern independently predicts cardiovascular events. When lateral ST depression is asymmetric, downsloping, and directed opposite a tall R wave, favor strain; when it is horizontal, dynamic, or accompanied by reciprocal change, do not dismiss ischemia."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Voltage-criteria examples and LV strain morphology.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — ventricular hypertrophy"}]}, {"id": "ischemia-infarction", "title": "Ischemia, Infarction, and Coronary Territories", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Acute coronary occlusion produces a wavefront of injury that faces some leads and points away from others. That geometry gives you both the ST elevation over the infarct and the reciprocal ST depression in the opposite leads, and it lets you name the culprit vessel from the lead grouping alone."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/de-winter.svg", "alt": "de Winter T waves", "caption": "de Winter pattern: upsloping ST depression with tall symmetric T waves in the precordial leads — an LAD-occlusion equivalent.", "credit": "Bron766 — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:De_Winter's_T_wave_(ECG).svg"}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Territory", "Leads with ST elevation", "Likely culprit", "Reciprocal / clue"], "rows": [["Septal", "V1-V2", "Proximal LAD", "-"], ["Anterior", "V2-V4", "LAD", "-"], ["Lateral", "I, aVL, V5-V6", "LCx or diagonal", "Inferior reciprocal (II, III, aVF)"], ["Inferior", "II, III, aVF", "RCA (about 80%) or LCx", "Reciprocal in I and aVL"], ["Right ventricular", "V4R (right-sided leads)", "Proximal RCA", "Inferior STEMI with hypotension, preload-sensitive"], ["Posterior", "Tall R and ST depression V1-V3", "RCA or LCx", "Confirm with V7-V9 posterior leads"]]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "items": ["Read the ST vector as a whole: which leads elevate and which depress, and whether they are anatomically opposed (true reciprocal) rather than diffuse.", "In any inferior STEMI, obtain right-sided leads (V4R) to catch RV involvement, because that changes management toward preload preservation and away from nitrates.", "In anterior ST depression, flip the tracing mentally and get posterior leads (V7-V9) — a posterior STEMI presents as ST depression on the standard 12 leads.", "Note diffuse ST depression with ST elevation in aVR, which suggests left-main or proximal LAD occlusion or severe three-vessel disease."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Isolated ST depression in V1-V3 with tall R waves is not anterior ischemia — it is the mirror image of a posterior STEMI. Missing it because there is no ST elevation on the standard leads is a classic, avoidable failure to reperfuse."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "The <strong>South African flag sign</strong> localizes a first-diagonal (high lateral) occlusion: ST elevation in I, aVL, and V2 with reciprocal ST depression in III forms a flag-shaped pattern on the standard limb-and-precordial layout. It is easy to under-call because aVL is under-read and V2 elevation is dismissed as anterior."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The field is moving from the STEMI/NSTEMI voltage dichotomy toward an occlusion-MI (OMI) paradigm, in which hyperacute T waves, de Winter changes, posterior MI, and a positive modified-Sgarbossa pattern are treated as acute coronary occlusion regardless of whether millimeter ST-elevation criteria are met. The disposition question is whether there is an occluded artery, not whether there is 1 mm of ST elevation."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Territory maps, reciprocal change, and infarct evolution examples.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — myocardial ischemia and infarction"}]}, {"id": "named-ischemic-signs", "title": "Named Ischemic Signs — The STEMI Equivalents", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "These are the patterns that decide whether a patient goes to the cath lab or gets sent home. Each is a specific wavefront signature of a specific high-risk lesion. Learn to describe them precisely, because their power is that they identify occlusion without meeting the crude millimeter rule."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/wellens.jpg", "alt": "Wellens syndrome ECG", "caption": "Wellens syndrome: deep symmetric or biphasic precordial T-wave inversion (pain-free) signaling critical proximal LAD stenosis.", "credit": "James Heilman, MD — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:WellensPainfree.JPG"}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "de Winter T waves", "def": "Upsloping ST depression of 1-3 mm at the J point in the precordial leads, continuing into tall, symmetric, peaked T waves in V1-V6, often with about 1 mm of ST elevation in aVR. A relatively static pattern (it may not evolve into overt ST elevation) that signals acute proximal LAD occlusion. Treat as a STEMI equivalent."}, {"term": "Wellens syndrome", "def": "Deeply and symmetrically inverted (Type B) or biphasic (Type A, initially positive then negative) T waves in V2-V3, sometimes extending across V1-V6, seen in a pain-free interval, with preserved R-wave progression, no pathologic Q waves, and little or no troponin rise. It marks a critical proximal LAD stenosis and a high risk of imminent anterior infarction."}, {"term": "Sgarbossa criteria", "def": "For diagnosing MI within an LBBB or ventricular-paced rhythm: (1) concordant ST elevation of 1 mm or more in a lead with a positive QRS (5 points); (2) concordant ST depression of 1 mm or more in V1-V3 (3 points); (3) discordant ST elevation of 5 mm or more (2 points). A score of 3 or more is specific for acute MI."}, {"term": "Modified Sgarbossa (Smith) criteria", "def": "Replaces the third original rule with a proportion: discordant ST elevation with an ST-to-S-wave ratio of -0.25 or more negative (the discordant ST elevation is at least 25% of the depth of the preceding S wave). This markedly improves sensitivity for occlusion MI in LBBB and paced rhythms while preserving specificity."}, {"term": "Spodick sign", "def": "Downsloping of the TP segment (the baseline between the T wave and the next P wave), best appreciated in lead II and the lateral precordial leads, supporting a diagnosis of acute pericarditis alongside diffuse concave ST elevation and PR-segment depression. Supportive, not specific."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Wellens syndrome is a warning shot, not a resolved event. Because the culprit is a critical proximal LAD stenosis, a provocative stress test can precipitate the very anterior infarction the pattern predicts. The correct next step is coronary angiography, not stress imaging."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "de Winter versus hyperkalemia: both give tall, peaked precordial T waves, but de Winter T waves are broad-based and symmetric with upsloping J-point ST depression in a patient with chest pain, whereas hyperkalemic T waves are narrow and tented with a normal or wide QRS and a metabolic context. When in doubt in chest pain, treat as occlusion and check a potassium in parallel."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The original Sgarbossa third criterion (discordant STE of 5 mm or more) is highly specific but poorly sensitive, which is exactly why Smith's proportional ST/S ratio replaced it. In practice, apply the modified rule lead by lead: find the lead with the deepest discordant S wave, and if the ST deviation in the same direction as the ST-segment shift reaches a quarter of that S-wave depth, call it positive and activate."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "de Winter, Wellens (Type A and B), Sgarbossa, and Spodick tracings with annotations.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — STEMI equivalents and named signs"}]}, {"id": "named-morphologic-signs", "title": "Named Morphologic Signs — Channelopathy, Structure, and Metabolism", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This second family of named signs is not about coronary occlusion but about inherited arrhythmia syndromes, structural disease, electrolyte derangement, and drug effect. Each is a near-pathognomonic shape once you know exactly what to look for and where."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/brugada.jpg", "alt": "Brugada type 1 ECG", "caption": "Type 1 Brugada pattern: coved ST elevation in V1–V2.", "credit": "PeaBrainC — CC BY-SA 4.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Brugada_syndrome_ECGs.jpg"}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Brugada pattern", "def": "Type 1 (diagnostic): coved ST elevation of 2 mm or more in one or more right precordial leads (V1-V2), with a descending ST segment continuing into a negative T wave. Type 2 (suggestive only): a saddleback ST elevation of 2 mm or more. Reflects an SCN5A-associated sodium channelopathy with risk of ventricular fibrillation and sudden death; unmasked by fever, sodium-channel blockers, and vagal tone."}, {"term": "Epsilon wave", "def": "A small positive deflection at the very end of the QRS, in the terminal notch just before the ST segment, in V1-V2. It represents delayed right-ventricular activation and is a hallmark of arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy (ARVC), often accompanied by T-wave inversion in V1-V3 and a prolonged terminal S-wave upstroke."}, {"term": "Osborn (J) wave", "def": "A positive deflection at the J point (the QRS-ST junction), the camel-hump or hathook, whose amplitude rises as core temperature falls. Classic in hypothermia; also seen in hypercalcemia and subarachnoid hemorrhage."}, {"term": "Electrical alternans", "def": "Beat-to-beat alternation in QRS amplitude (sometimes of P and T as well) caused by the heart swinging within a large volume of pericardial fluid. Total electrical alternans (P-QRS-T) with sinus tachycardia is highly suggestive of a large effusion with tamponade physiology."}, {"term": "Ashman phenomenon", "def": "An aberrantly conducted beat (usually RBBB morphology) that terminates a short RR cycle which was itself preceded by a long RR cycle. The long-short sequence exploits the rate-dependence of refractoriness; commonly seen in atrial fibrillation and frequently misread as a premature ventricular complex."}, {"term": "Prominent U waves", "def": "A small deflection following the T wave, in the same direction, most visible in the mid-precordial leads. Prominent U waves with T-wave flattening and ST depression are a signature of hypokalemia; also seen with bradycardia, hypothermia, LVH, and CNS events."}, {"term": "Digoxin effect", "def": "Down-sloping, scooped or sagging ST depression (the Salvador Dali mustache or reverse-tick), a shortened QT, flattened or inverted T waves, and increased U-wave amplitude, often with mild PR prolongation. This is a therapeutic-level effect and must be distinguished from digoxin toxicity, which produces arrhythmias."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "Sign-to-disease shortcut: coved V1-V2 elevation equals Brugada (channelopathy); terminal V1 notch equals epsilon equals ARVC (structure); J-point hump equals Osborn equals hypothermia (metabolic); swinging QRS amplitude equals tamponade (mechanical); U waves equal hypokalemia (electrolyte); scooped ST equals digoxin (drug). One shape, one diagnosis."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Digoxin <strong>effect</strong> is expected at therapeutic levels and needs no action, but digoxin <strong>toxicity</strong> is an arrhythmia diagnosis: paroxysmal atrial tachycardia with block, accelerated junctional rhythm, and the near-pathognomonic bidirectional ventricular tachycardia. Hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia potentiate toxicity, and the antidote for life-threatening toxicity is digoxin-specific antibody fragments."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Only the Brugada type 1 (coved) pattern is diagnostic; a type 2 saddleback is a finding that requires either conversion to type 1 (spontaneously, with fever, or on a sodium-channel-blocker challenge) plus a clinical or family risk profile before it carries the same weight. Never diagnose Brugada syndrome off a single asymptomatic saddleback in isolation."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Brugada types 1 and 2, epsilon wave, Osborn wave, electrical alternans, U waves, and digoxin effect galleries.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — morphologic and channelopathy signs"}]}, {"id": "electrolytes-drugs", "title": "Electrolyte and Drug Effects", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Metabolic and pharmacologic effects on the ECG are testable and, more importantly, actionable at the bedside. Potassium in particular produces a stereotyped, escalating sequence that lets you estimate its severity and urgency from the tracing, though the exact number should still be confirmed."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "items": ["<strong>Hyperkalemia:</strong> peaked, narrow, tented T waves first; then PR prolongation and P-wave flattening; then QRS widening; finally a sine-wave pattern and asystole.", "<strong>Hypokalemia:</strong> T-wave flattening, ST depression, and increasingly prominent U waves, with a long apparent QU interval and predisposition to torsades.", "<strong>Hypercalcemia:</strong> short QT (short ST segment); severe cases show Osborn-like J waves.", "<strong>Hypocalcemia:</strong> long QT driven by a prolonged ST segment, with a normal T-wave width."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "ECG changes of hyperkalemia are a medical emergency independent of the exact potassium number. A widening QRS or sine-wave pattern demands immediate intravenous calcium to stabilize the myocardium, followed by insulin-glucose, beta-agonist, and definitive potassium removal. Do not wait for a repeat laboratory value to act on a sine wave."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Drug", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Digoxin", "0.125-0.25 mg PO daily (lower for renal impairment, elderly)", "Serum level 0.5-0.9 ng/mL in HFrEF (DIG trial)", "Advanced AV block without pacer, WPW with AF, hypokalemia", "Level, K, Mg, renal function, ECG"], ["Magnesium sulfate (for TdP)", "2 g IV over 1-2 min", "Repeat 2 g; infusion for recurrence", "Caution in renal failure and heart block", "Reflexes, level, telemetry"], ["Sotalol (class III)", "80 mg PO BID (renally adjusted)", "Up to 120-160 mg BID by QT tolerance", "CrCl low, baseline QTc above 450 ms, decompensated HF", "Inpatient QTc, renal function, HR"], ["Dofetilide (class III)", "500 mcg PO BID (CrCl/QTc adjusted)", "Per renal function and QTc protocol", "CrCl under 20 mL/min, QTc above 440 ms baseline or above 500 ms on therapy", "Mandatory inpatient QTc monitoring for three days, K, Mg"], ["Amiodarone", "Load 150 mg IV then infusion; PO load 400 mg BID-TID", "PO maintenance 200 mg daily", "Iodine allergy; caution with long QT and thyroid/lung/liver disease", "QTc, TFTs, LFTs, PFTs, ophthalmology"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Amiodarone prolongs the QT but rarely causes torsades, an apparent paradox explained by its homogeneous prolongation of repolarization and multichannel blockade, which limits the transmural dispersion that seeds torsades. This is why a moderately long QTc on amiodarone is tolerated in ways it would not be on sotalol or dofetilide — but a QTc pushing 500 ms still demands attention and electrolyte optimization."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Hyperkalemia progression, hypokalemia with U waves, and calcium-related QT changes.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — electrolyte abnormalities"}]}, {"id": "wide-complex-tachycardia", "title": "Wide-Complex Tachycardia — VT versus SVT", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "A regular wide-complex tachycardia is ventricular tachycardia until proven otherwise, and the base-rate reasoning matters: in a patient with structural heart disease or prior infarction, the large majority of wide-complex tachycardias are VT. Misclassifying VT as SVT with aberrancy and giving a calcium-channel blocker can be catastrophic."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "items": ["<strong>AV dissociation</strong> — independent P waves marching through the tachycardia — strongly favors VT.", "<strong>Capture and fusion beats</strong> — an occasional narrow or hybrid complex from an intermittently conducted sinus beat — are nearly diagnostic of VT.", "<strong>Extreme (northwest) axis</strong> and a very broad QRS (above 140 ms in an RBBB pattern, above 160 ms in an LBBB pattern) favor VT.", "<strong>Precordial concordance</strong> — all precordial QRS complexes entirely positive or entirely negative — favors VT."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Do not give a nodal-blocking calcium-channel blocker (verapamil or diltiazem) to an undifferentiated wide-complex tachycardia. If it is VT, you can precipitate hemodynamic collapse. When the rhythm is unstable, cardiovert; when stable and the diagnosis is uncertain, treat as VT."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Agent", "Role", "Dose", "Key caution"], "rows": [["Adenosine", "Diagnose/terminate regular narrow SVT; unmask flutter", "6 mg rapid IV push, then 12 mg", "Avoid in asthma/COPD bronchospasm; transplanted (denervated) hearts are supersensitive, so reduce the dose; unhelpful and potentially risky in true VT"], ["Amiodarone", "Stable VT, electrical storm", "150 mg IV over 10 min, then infusion", "Hypotension, QT prolongation"], ["Procainamide", "Stable monomorphic VT (favored over amiodarone in the PROCAMIO trial)", "Loading infusion to effect", "Hypotension, QRS/QT widening, avoid in severe LV dysfunction"], ["Synchronized cardioversion", "Unstable VT/SVT with a pulse", "Energy per device, sedate if possible", "Ensure sync mode; defibrillate pulseless or polymorphic VT"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Adenosine doubles as a diagnostic tool: in a regular narrow tachycardia it either terminates AVNRT/AVRT (confirming a re-entrant SVT) or transiently blocks the AV node to reveal underlying flutter or atrial tachycardia. In a genuinely wide, regular tachycardia it is usually unrevealing and should not substitute for treating VT."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "VT versus SVT-with-aberrancy examples, fusion/capture beats, and the Brugada algorithm.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — broad complex tachycardia"}]}, {"id": "pericardial-tamponade", "title": "Pericarditis, Effusion, and Tamponade on the ECG", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The pericardial syndromes have a recognizable ECG arc from inflammation to fluid to hemodynamic compromise, and each stage has a named sign. The value is in separating pericarditis from acute MI, and in reading a large effusion before the echo arrives."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/electrical-alternans.jpg", "alt": "Electrical alternans", "caption": "Electrical alternans with low voltage and tachycardia in a large pericardial effusion.", "credit": "James Heilman, MD — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Electrical_Alternans.JPG"}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["<strong>Acute pericarditis:</strong> diffuse, concave-upward ST elevation across multiple territories with <strong>PR-segment depression</strong> and PR elevation in aVR, without reciprocal change and without the anatomic grouping of a STEMI.", "<strong>Spodick sign:</strong> downsloping of the TP baseline, a supportive marker of pericarditis.", "<strong>Large effusion / tamponade:</strong> low QRS voltage and <strong>electrical alternans</strong>, ideally the total (P-QRS-T) form, with sinus tachycardia."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "Pericarditis versus STEMI: pericarditis gives diffuse ST elevation that does not respect a coronary territory, has PR depression, lacks reciprocal ST depression (except aVR and V1), and does not form Q waves or lose R waves. When ST elevation is regional with reciprocal change, it is occlusion until proven otherwise — err toward the artery."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "text": "Low voltage plus electrical alternans plus sinus tachycardia in a dyspneic, hypotensive patient is tamponade until an echo says otherwise. This is a clinical and echocardiographic diagnosis; the treatment is pericardiocentesis, and the ECG is the clue that gets you there quickly."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Pericarditis stages, Spodick sign, and electrical alternans tracings.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — pericarditis and effusion"}]}, {"id": "pitfalls-pearls", "title": "High-Yield Pitfalls and Fellowship Pearls", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Always finish the sequence: the lethal finding is often the second abnormality, not the first.", "Get serial tracings in chest pain — a static single ECG can miss an evolving occlusion.", "Compare with priors: a new LBBB, a new axis shift, or new T-wave inversions carry weight that old ones do not.", "Lead misplacement and artifact mimic pathology; check lead placement before diagnosing dextrocardia, extreme axis, or asystole.", "Do not include a U wave in the QT, and do not diagnose long QT off a single fast-rate Bazett value."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "aVR is the most under-read lead. ST elevation in aVR with diffuse ST depression elsewhere flags left-main or proximal LAD occlusion or severe three-vessel disease; PR elevation in aVR supports pericarditis; and a positive terminal R wave in aVR is a marker of sodium-channel-blocker toxicity. Read it every time."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The unifying fellowship habit is provenance: for every abnormal deflection, ask what wavefront in what tissue at what time produces it, and whether the rest of the tracing is consistent with that mechanism. A de Winter pattern, a Brugada type 1, and a Sgarbossa-positive LBBB are all deductions from that same question — and that is how you avoid the two failure modes, over-calling benign variants and under-calling silent occlusion."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 54-year-old man with hypertension and a 30-pack-year smoking history presents with 40 minutes of crushing substernal chest pain. His ECG shows 2 mm of upsloping ST depression at the J point in V2-V6, continuing into tall, symmetric, peaked T waves, with 1 mm of ST elevation in aVR. There is no ST elevation meeting standard criteria in the precordial leads. Serum potassium returns at 4.2 mmol/L. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Administer intravenous calcium gluconate for presumed hyperkalemia"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Activate the cardiac catheterization laboratory for emergent angiography"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Obtain a treadmill stress test to evaluate for inducible ischemia"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Start a heparin drip and admit for serial troponins and a next-day ECG"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Give sublingual nitroglycerin and reassure if the pain resolves"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is the de Winter T-wave pattern: upsloping J-point ST depression with tall, symmetric, peaked precordial T waves and reciprocal ST elevation in aVR, a relatively static STEMI-equivalent of acute proximal LAD occlusion. It mandates emergent reperfusion despite the absence of classic ST elevation. The normal potassium and the chest-pain context exclude hyperkalemia (whose T waves are narrow and tented), and stress testing or a wait-and-see admission would dangerously delay opening an occluded artery."}, {"stem": "A 71-year-old woman with a known left bundle branch block presents with acute chest pain. Her ECG shows the LBBB with 2 mm of ST elevation in leads III and aVF that is concordant with a predominantly positive QRS in those leads. Which finding best supports acute myocardial infarction?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Discordant ST elevation of 3 mm in V2, where the QRS is predominantly negative"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Concordant ST elevation of 1 mm or more in a lead with a positive QRS"}, {"key": "C", "text": "A QRS duration of 140 ms"}, {"key": "D", "text": "T-wave inversion in the lateral precordial leads"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Appropriate discordance of the ST segment throughout"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "By the Sgarbossa criteria, concordant ST elevation of at least 1 mm in a lead with a positive QRS scores 5 points and is highly specific for acute MI within an LBBB. Discordant ST elevation only counts when it is large (5 mm or more in the original criteria, or an ST/S ratio of at least -0.25 by the modified Smith criterion), so 3 mm of discordant elevation is not itself diagnostic. QRS width, lateral T inversion, and appropriate discordance are expected features of uncomplicated LBBB and do not indicate infarction."}, {"stem": "A 48-year-old man had two episodes of exertional chest pain over the past week and is now pain-free in the emergency department. His initial troponin is at the upper reference limit, and his ECG shows biphasic T waves in V2 and V3 (initially positive then negative) with preserved R-wave progression and no ST elevation or pathologic Q waves. What is the most appropriate management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Exercise treadmill stress test to risk-stratify before discharge"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Discharge with outpatient cardiology follow-up given the pain-free state"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Coronary angiography given a likely high-grade proximal LAD lesion"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Reassurance and a repeat ECG in six weeks"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Empiric pericarditis treatment with NSAIDs and colchicine"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "Biphasic (Type A) or deeply inverted (Type B) T waves in V2-V3 during a pain-free interval, with preserved R waves and minimal biomarker rise, define Wellens syndrome, which signals a critical proximal LAD stenosis and imminent risk of a large anterior infarction. The correct step is angiography. Provocative stress testing is specifically hazardous because it can trigger the very infarction the pattern predicts, and discharge or a pericarditis pathway would miss a high-risk lesion."}, {"stem": "A 33-year-old woman is admitted for pneumonia and started on levofloxacin and ondansetron. She is hypokalemic at 3.0 mmol/L. On telemetry she develops recurrent, self-terminating polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a twisting axis, and her baseline QTc is 520 ms. Which is the most appropriate immediate intervention?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Intravenous amiodarone bolus and infusion"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Intravenous magnesium sulfate 2 g and potassium repletion"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Oral sotalol to suppress the ventricular ectopy"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Intravenous procainamide loading"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Immediate synchronized cardioversion at 50 J"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is torsades de pointes from an acquired long QT, potentiated by two QT-prolonging drugs (a fluoroquinolone and ondansetron) plus hypokalemia. First-line treatment is intravenous magnesium 2 g regardless of the serum magnesium level, aggressive potassium repletion to 4.5-5 mmol/L, and withdrawal of the offending agents. Additional QT-prolonging antiarrhythmics such as amiodarone, sotalol, or procainamide would worsen the substrate. Synchronized cardioversion is reserved for sustained or hemodynamically unstable episodes; for pause-dependent recurrence, rate acceleration with isoproterenol or overdrive pacing is used."}, {"stem": "An 80-year-old man presents with recurrent presyncope. His ECG shows a sinus rate of 78 with a constant PR interval, a wide QRS, and intermittent single non-conducted P waves that occur without any preceding PR-interval lengthening. There is no reversible cause. What is the most appropriate management?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Reassurance, as this is benign Mobitz I (Wenckebach) block"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Atropine as definitive long-term therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Permanent pacemaker implantation"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Observation with an outpatient event monitor only"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Start a beta-blocker to stabilize the conduction system"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "A fixed PR interval with sudden non-conducted P waves and no preceding PR prolongation, especially with a wide QRS, is Mobitz II second-degree AV block. It localizes to the infranodal His-Purkinje system, is unstable, does not respond reliably to atropine, and progresses unpredictably to complete heart block. In a symptomatic patient without a reversible cause it is a Class I indication for permanent pacing. Wenckebach (progressive PR prolongation before a dropped beat) is nodal and usually benign, and a beta-blocker would worsen conduction."}, {"stem": "A previously healthy 26-year-old man is found unresponsive after a syncopal episode and recovers spontaneously. He reports a febrile illness over the past two days. His ECG shows coved ST-segment elevation of 3 mm in V1 and V2 that descends into an inverted T wave, with a normal QT and no ST elevation elsewhere. His father died suddenly at age 40. Which statement is most accurate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "This is a saddleback type 2 Brugada pattern and is non-diagnostic"}, {"key": "B", "text": "This is a diagnostic type 1 Brugada pattern, and fever likely unmasked it"}, {"key": "C", "text": "The findings represent normal early repolarization in a young athlete"}, {"key": "D", "text": "The pattern indicates acute anteroseptal STEMI requiring reperfusion"}, {"key": "E", "text": "This is an epsilon-wave pattern diagnostic of ARVC"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Coved (downsloping) ST elevation of 2 mm or more in the right precordial leads descending into an inverted T wave is the diagnostic type 1 Brugada pattern of an SCN5A-associated sodium channelopathy, associated with ventricular fibrillation and sudden death. Fever is a classic unmasking trigger, and the syncope plus family history of early sudden death raise the risk substantially. A saddleback morphology would be the non-diagnostic type 2 pattern. The regional coved change without reciprocal findings and the normal QT argue against STEMI, and an epsilon wave is a terminal QRS notch of ARVC, a different entity."}, {"stem": "A 68-year-old man with atrial fibrillation is on telemetry when a single wide QRS complex with right bundle branch block morphology appears. It ends a short RR interval that was immediately preceded by a longer RR interval, and the surrounding rhythm is otherwise unchanged. What does this most likely represent?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A premature ventricular complex requiring antiarrhythmic therapy"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Ashman phenomenon, an aberrantly conducted supraventricular beat"}, {"key": "C", "text": "An epsilon wave indicating arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Onset of ventricular tachycardia requiring cardioversion"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Intermittent Mobitz II block"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "A single aberrantly conducted beat, usually with RBBB morphology, that terminates a short RR cycle preceded by a long RR cycle is the Ashman phenomenon. The long-short sequence exploits the rate-dependence of His-Purkinje refractoriness, so a supraventricular impulse conducts aberrantly rather than arising ectopically from the ventricle. It is common in atrial fibrillation and is frequently misread as a PVC, but it does not by itself indicate ventricular ectopy, structural disease, or a need for antiarrhythmic or cardioversion therapy."}]};
